    intro: 'Claiming an FTA preference (like KORUS or CAFTA-DR) instantly lowers your costs, but it puts a target on your back. CBP loves to audit these claims. If you can\'t prove origin, you pay.',
    services: 'FTA preferences deliver substantial duty savings—but only if your origin documentation withstands CBP verification. We conduct rules of origin analyses including tariff shift determinations and regional value content calculations for USMCA, KORUS, CAFTA-DR, AUSFTA, and other agreements. Our team audits supplier certificates of origin, prepares defense packages for CBP CF-28 verifications, and implements yarn-forward traceability for textiles. Working with foreign manufacturers, we collect confidential production data while protecting trade secrets. Capture duty savings without audit risk or penalty exposure. Schedule your FTA qualification review.',
    keywords: 'free trade agreement attorney California, FTA compliance lawyer, KORUS attorney California, CAFTA-DR lawyer, FTA verification defense attorney, certificate of origin lawyer California, tariff preference attorney, FTA audit defense California, yarn forward attorney, regional value content FTA lawyer, usmca attorney california, usmca lawyer california, usmca california, free trade agreement lawyer california, free trade agreement california',
        publishedDate: '2025-11-22',
        lastModified: '2025-11-22',
        content: `
      <h2>The Privilege of Preference</h2>
      <p>Utilizing a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) - such as KORUS (Korea), CAFTA-DR (Central America), or AUSFTA (Australia) - is the most effective way to reduce landed cost. But importers often treat it as a given. "It came from Korea, so it's duty-free." This is legally wrong. To qualify, the good must meet specific Rules of Origin. It usually requires a "Tariff Shift" (transforming raw materials) or a specific Regional Value Content (RVC). If you claim the preference without doing the math, you are committing negligence.</p>
      <h2>Legal Framework for FTA Preferences</h2>
      <p>Free trade agreement (FTA) preferences are implemented through a combination of statutory authorizations and detailed regulatory requirements. Congress authorizes FTA implementation through specific legislation, such as the USMCA Implementation Act at 19 U.S.C. § 4501 et seq., and delegates rulemaking authority to CBP under 19 U.S.C. § 1202(a). Each FTA contains product-specific rules of origin codified in harmonized regulations: USMCA rules appear at 19 C.F.R. Part 182, CAFTA-DR rules at 19 C.F.R. Part 10.2031, and KORUS rules at 19 C.F.R. Part 10.3001. California importers claiming preferential duty treatment must possess a valid certification meeting 19 C.F.R. § 182.12 (USMCA) or equivalent FTA-specific requirements. CBP may verify origin claims under 19 C.F.R. § 182.72 through importer questionnaires, plant visits, or foreign government cooperation. False or erroneous FTA claims expose importers to penalty liability under 19 U.S.C. § 1592, duty rate advances under 19 U.S.C. § 1514, and potential denial of future preferential treatment.</p>
      

      <h2>The Supplier Disconnect</h2>
      <p>Most FTA errors stem from relying on a vendor's affidavit without verification. Suppliers often sign Certificates of Origin just to get the sale, without understanding the legal criteria. They might confuse "Made in Korea" (marking) with "Korea Originating" (FTA). These are different standards. When CBP audits you, <em>you</em> are on the hook for the back duties and penalties, not the supplier. We audit your high-volume items, tracing the Bill of Materials back to the raw materials to ensure the "Originating" claim stands up to scrutiny.</p>

      <h2>Textiles and "Yarn Forward"</h2>
      <p>For the apparel industry, FTAs like CAFTA-DR rely on the "Yarn Forward" rule. The yarn must be spun in the region to qualify. This requires supply chain visibility all the way back to the spinning mill. We help textile importers map this chain and collect the necessary affidavits to prove compliance.</p>

      <h2>Defending the Verification</h2>
      <p>When CBP sends a Request for Information (CF-28) challenging an FTA claim, the clock starts ticking. You need to produce the production records, affidavits, and cost breakdowns immediately. We manage this response process. We know what CBP auditors look for and how to present complex manufacturing data in a way that checks their boxes. We often work directly with the foreign factory to sanitize data, ensuring their trade secrets are protected while CBP gets the proof they need to close the audit with a "No Change" determination.</p>
    `
