        publishedDate: '2025-11-21',
        lastModified: '2025-11-21',
        content: `
      <h2>The Rebuttable Presumption</h2>
      <p>The Uyghur Forced Labor Prevention Act (UFLPA) fundamentally changed U.S. import law. Previously, CBP had to find evidence of forced labor to stop goods. Now, if your supply chain touches the Xinjiang Uyghur Autonomous Region (XUAR) - or involves high-risk commodities like cotton, polysilicon, or tomatoes from China - CBP presumes they are banned. The burden shifts entirely to you to prove a negative: that no forced labor was used at any stage of production. This is one of the hardest challenges in modern trade compliance.</p>
      <h2>Legal Prohibitions on Forced Labor Imports</h2>
      <p>Federal law absolutely prohibits importation of goods mined, produced, or manufactured wholly or in part using forced labor under 19 U.S.C. § 1307. The Uyghur Forced Labor Prevention Act (UFLPA), enacted in 2021, created a rebuttable presumption that goods from Xinjiang, China, or produced by entities on the UFLPA Entity List are made with forced labor and therefore prohibited under 19 U.S.C. § 1307. CBP enforces forced labor prohibitions through detention and exclusion procedures codified at 19 C.F.R. § 12.42, which authorizes CBP to detain shipments when information reasonably indicates forced labor. The Trade Facilitation and Trade Enforcement Act of 2015 (TFTEA) closed the consumptive demand loophole, making the prohibition absolute regardless of domestic production. California importers receiving CBP Form 28 detention notices must respond within 30 days under 19 C.F.R. § 12.43, providing substantial evidence demonstrating the supply chain is free from forced labor indicators. Knowingly importing forced labor goods triggers penalties under 19 U.S.C. § 1592 and potential criminal liability.</p>
      

      <h2>Supply Chain Mapping and Traceability</h2>
      <p>To get goods released, you need to map the supply chain all the way back to the raw materials. Who grew the cotton? Who spun the yarn? Who mined the silica? We help clients build these "Traceability Packages." We collect affidavits, production records, transportation documents, and payment records for every step of the process. We organize this data to create an unbroken chain of custody that withstands CBP scrutiny.</p>

      <h2>Detention Response</h2>
      <p>If your goods are detained under the UFLPA, you typically have 30 days to respond. Speed is critical. We immediately engage with the Center of Excellence and Expertise (CEE) to determine the specific scope of the detention. We then deploy our traceability data to argue for release ("Admissibility Review"). The standard of proof is "clear and convincing evidence," which is higher than a standard civil case. We know how to frame the evidence to meet this high bar.</p>

      <h2>The Entity List</h2>
      <p>The UFLPA Entity List names specific companies that are banned from the U.S. supply chain. However, dealing with their subsidiaries or affiliates is also dangerous. We conduct deep due diligence on your suppliers to ensure you aren't inadvertently sourcing from a blacklisted entity or a "downstream" affiliate that triggers a detention.</p>


      <h2>Forced Labor Prevention Checklist</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Supplier Contracts:</strong> Include forced labor prohibition clause with: right to audit, requirement for subcontractor disclosure, termination rights if violations found.</li>
        <li><strong>Risk Indicators:</strong> Red flags: recruitment fees charged to workers, passport confiscation, restricted movement, below-minimum wages, excessive overtime, poor living conditions.</li>
        <li><strong>Due Diligence Procedure:</strong> Annual third-party audit addressing ILO forced labor indicators. Quarterly self-assessment questionnaire. Unannounced audits for high-risk suppliers.</li>
        <li><strong>Remediation Protocol:</strong> If indicators found: immediate corrective action plan required within 30 days. Verify remediation within 90 days. Terminate if not corrected.</li>
      </ul>
    `
