    id: 'ear-compliance',
    title: 'Export Administration Regulations',
    subheading: 'Dual-Use Controls for Technology and Software.',
    intro: 'You don\'t have to make missiles to violate export laws. For California\'s technology, semiconductor, aerospace, and manufacturing sectors concentrated in Silicon Valley, Los Angeles, and San Diego, Export Administration Regulations compliance is critical to avoiding catastrophic export violations and criminal prosecution. If you export encryption software, sensors, or advanced electronics, you are likely subject to the EAR. BIS enforcement is ramping up.',
    services: 'Export Administration Regulations violations can result in export privilege denial—ending your global market access. We perform ECCN classifications using the Commerce Control List, prepare export license applications under SNAP-R, implement automated Entity List screening in ERP systems, conduct red flag training for export personnel, and defend California technology companies against BIS enforcement actions. Working with engineers, we properly classify encryption software, semiconductors, and telecommunications equipment while documenting defensible rationales. Maintain global market access while avoiding catastrophic enforcement outcomes. Request ECCN classification assistance or BIS enforcement defense.',
    keywords: 'EAR attorney California, export administration regulations lawyer, ECCN classification attorney, BIS compliance lawyer California, dual-use export attorney, entity list screening lawyer California, EAR violation defense attorney, export license lawyer California, SNAP-R attorney, export controls California, itar attorney california, itar lawyer california, itar california, ear lawyer california, ear california',
        publishedDate: '2025-11-21',
        lastModified: '2025-11-21',
        content: `
      <h2>It's Not Just Military Gear</h2>
      <p>The Export Administration Regulations (EAR), managed by the Bureau of Industry and Security (BIS), control "dual-use" items. These are commercial goods that <em>could</em> have military or strategic applications. Many companies assume their commercial tech is EAR99 (no license required), only to find out it falls under a specific Export Control Classification Number (ECCN) due to a new processor, sensor, or encryption algorithm. Exporting these items to China, Russia, or even friendly nations without a license can lead to severe penalties.</p>
      <h2>The Reasonable Care Statutory Standard</h2>
      <p>The Customs Modernization Act (Mod Act) of 1993 amended 19 U.S.C. § 1484 to impose an affirmative "reasonable care" obligation on importers. This statute requires importers to use reasonable care to enter, classify, and value imported merchandise, and to provide any other information necessary to enable CBP to properly assess duties and determine admissibility. Reasonable care is not defined in the statute; instead, CBP articulates the standard through its Informed Compliance Publication "What Every Member of the Trade Community Should Know About: Reasonable Care." The standard is flexible and fact-specific, requiring importers to take steps proportional to the complexity of their imports, volume of entries, and known compliance risks. California importers must implement internal controls, conduct periodic self-audits, maintain adequate recordkeeping under 19 U.S.C. § 1509, and correct errors through prior disclosure under 19 U.S.C. § 1592(c)(4) when violations are discovered. Failure to exercise reasonable care supports penalty liability under 19 U.S.C. § 1592(a), with CBP using control failures as evidence of at least negligence.</p>
      

      <h2>Classification is Key</h2>
      <p>Compliance starts with the ECCN. Determining this requires a technical analysis of the Commerce Control List (CCL). Category 5 (Encryption) and Category 3 (Electronics) are particularly complex. If you get the ECCN wrong, you trigger the wrong licensing requirements. We work with your engineers to classify items correctly, documenting the rationale (the "Classification Matrix") to protect you in an audit.</p>

      <h2>The Entity List and End-Use Checks</h2>
      <p>Even harmless goods (EAR99) cannot be shipped to bad actors. The BIS Entity List is growing rapidly, especially with Chinese and Russian firms. Shipping <em>anything</em> to a listed entity without a license is a violation. Furthermore, you cannot ship items if you "know" they will be used for a prohibited end-use (like military intelligence in China). We help clients integrate automated screening tools into their ERP systems and develop "Red Flag" checklists to catch these orders before they ship.</p>

      <h2>Enforcement Defense</h2>
      <p>If BIS sends a Charging Letter or a Subpoena, the risks are existential. Fines can reach $300,000 per violation or twice the value of the transaction. We negotiate with the Office of Export Enforcement (OEE) to settle cases. By presenting a strong compliance narrative, conducting a thorough internal investigation, and cooperating with the government, we aim to reduce penalties and avoid the "death penalty" - denial of export privileges.</p>


      <h2>EAR Compliance Program Essentials</h2>
      <p><strong>ECCN Classification Process (Critical First Step):</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Step 1:</strong> Gather technical specs: encryption algorithms/key lengths, performance parameters (speed/frequency/accuracy), technical descriptions.</li>
        <li><strong>Step 2:</strong> Review Commerce Control List (CCL) systematically by category. Common categories: Cat 3 (Electronics), Cat 4 (Computers), Cat 5 (Telecom/Encryption), Cat 6 (Sensors).</li>
        <li><strong>Step 3:</strong> Document classification rationale in writing. Retain for 5 years. Update when product specs change.</li>
        <li><strong>Step 4:</strong> For complex items, request official ECCN classification from BIS (60-90 day process but provides certainty).</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Entity List Screening Protocol:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>Daily downloads of BIS Entity List, Denied Persons List, Unverified List from bis.doc.gov</li>
        <li>Automated screening integrated into: order entry, shipping, customer onboarding systems</li>
        <li>Enhanced due diligence for high-risk countries: China, Russia, Iran—verify end-user and end-use</li>
        <li>Red flag training for sales teams: customer evasiveness, requests to falsify documents, unusual routing</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Export License Application Timeline:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>Prepare application via BIS SNAP-R system including: item specs, ECCN, end-user, end-use, destination country</li>
        <li>Processing time: 2-4 months for most applications; longer for complex/sensitive items</li>
        <li>License exceptions available for certain low-risk scenarios (ENC for encryption, TMP for temporary exports)</li>
      </ul>
    `
