    intro: 'Section 321 de minimis reform represents the most significant shift in e-commerce import regulation since the threshold increased from $200 to $800 in 2016, and now faces potential elimination or reduction under Congressional scrutiny. For California e-commerce businesses, third-party logistics providers, and cross-border fulfillment operations handling millions of Type 86 entries annually through Los Angeles, Long Beach, and San Francisco processing centers, proposed Section 321 reforms threaten fundamental business models. The proposed legislation eliminating Section 321 for China-origin goods or reducing the threshold back to $200 would devastate California\'s e-commerce fulfillment industry handling direct-to-consumer shipments. California companies must understand how proposed reforms would impact operations, evaluate compliance costs under potential new regimes, and prepare contingency strategies. Our firm monitors Section 321 reform legislation, advises California e-commerce businesses on strategic responses to proposed changes, and develops compliance frameworks adapting to evolving regulatory requirements.',
