  subheading: 'Molds, dies, and engineering valuation for California manufacturers importing production goods.',
  intro: 'When California manufacturers provide tooling, molds, dies, or engineering work to overseas suppliers for use in producing imported goods, U.S. Customs requires these "assists" to be added to the transaction value under 19 U.S.C. § 1401a(b)(1)(C). Failure to properly declare and apportion assist values triggers customs valuation audits, retroactive duty assessments, and potential penalties. California companies in automotive, electronics, medical device, and consumer goods sectors frequently provide substantial assists to Chinese, Mexican, and Vietnamese contract manufacturers without understanding the customs implications. The assist valuation rules require allocation of tool costs across units produced, proper accounting for engineering services, and accurate reporting of materials furnished. CBP actively audits assist compliance through Focused Assessments. Our firm quantifies assist values, develops allocation methodologies, and defends California manufacturers during CBP assist audits.',
  services: 'Trembach Law Firm assists California manufacturers with assist valuation compliance including proper identification of assists such as molds, dies, tooling, and engineering work provided to foreign manufacturers, accurate apportionment methodologies, audit defense when CBP discovers undeclared assists, prior disclosure filings when internal audits identify failures, and implementation of prospective tracking procedures. Assist valuation is the most commonly missed compliance obligation for California companies manufacturing in China, Mexico, and Vietnam. Failure to declare assists can result in substantial penalties. Contact us for assist compliance review and CBP audit defense.',
