  id: 'section-1592-penalties-california-defense',
  title: '19 USC 1592 Penalties California Defense',
  subheading: 'Understanding Negligence, Gross Negligence, and Fraud Standards in Customs Penalty Cases',
  intro: 'California importers face substantial monetary penalties under 19 USC 1592 for customs violations at the ports of Los Angeles, Long Beach, Oakland, and San Francisco. The statute imposes liability for entering merchandise through material false statements or omissions, with penalty amounts determined by culpability: negligence (two times duties lost), gross negligence (four times duties lost), or fraud (domestic value of merchandise). Distinguishing between culpability levels becomes critical when defending against CBP penalty notices that can reach millions of dollars. California\'s technology, automotive, and consumer goods importers must understand how CBP assesses culpability based on the totality of circumstances, including compliance history and sophistication. The Pre-Penalty Notice process under 19 CFR § 162.79 provides limited opportunity to present evidence mitigating culpability findings. Our firm defends California importers against Section 1592 penalties and negotiates penalty mitigation.',
  services: 'Trembach Law Firm defends California importers against 19 USC Section 1592 civil penalty allegations involving material false statements at all culpability levels including negligence, gross negligence, and fraud. We respond to Pre-Penalty Notices with detailed defenses challenging materiality and culpability, file strategic Prior Disclosures eliminating penalty exposure, prepare comprehensive Petitions for Mitigation presenting mitigating factors, negotiate Offers in Compromise, and defend determinations through administrative appeals. We develop prior disclosure strategies and negotiate penalty mitigation under 19 CFR Part 171. We represent clients through pre-penalty proceedings, petition processes, and supplemental petitions to achieve optimal penalty reductions. Contact us immediately upon receiving Pre-Penalty Notice or discovering potential violations.',
