  intro: 'When U.S. Customs and Border Protection seizes commercial cargo at California ports, importers face significant financial losses and supply chain disruptions requiring immediate legal intervention. Understanding the distinction between detention and seizure, navigating complex forfeiture proceedings under 19 USC § 1595a, and executing timely petition strategies under 19 CFR Part 162 determines whether detained merchandise can be recovered. California importers handling seized cargo at ports from Long Beach to Oakland must file claims within 30 days and petitions for relief within 20 additional days to preserve appeal rights. Seizures stem from allegations of trademark infringement, FDA violations, prohibited merchandise restrictions, undervaluation, or false country of origin claims. The burden shifts to importers to prove merchandise is not subject to forfeiture. Our firm provides immediate legal response, files claims and petitions, and litigates forfeiture cases.',
  services: 'Trembach Law Firm provides aggressive defense for California importers facing CBP seizure and forfeiture actions involving intellectual property allegations, false country of origin, prohibited merchandise, and UFLPA forced labor violations. We respond to Notices of Seizure challenging probable cause, file timely Claims and Cost Bonds preventing administrative forfeiture, prepare Petitions for Remission or Mitigation presenting lack of knowledge defenses, negotiate administrative settlements recovering seized goods, and defend judicial forfeiture proceedings in federal court. Time is critical in seizure cases. Contact us immediately upon seizure to preserve legal rights.',
  keywords: ['CBP seizure defense California', 'customs forfeiture attorney', 'detained cargo recovery', 'petition for relief', '19 USC 1595a', 'administrative forfeiture', 'judicial forfeiture defense', 'California port seizures', 'customs penalty mitigation', 'supersedeas bond', 'CBP detention appeals', 'forfeiture proceedings', 'seized merchandise recovery', 'customs violation defense', 'import compliance'],
