  intro: 'The False Claims Act at 31 U.S.C. §§ 3729-3733 has emerged as a formidable enforcement tool in customs litigation, particularly through qui tam whistleblower actions. With FCA penalties reaching treble damages plus civil penalties of up to $28,619 per claim, importers and customs brokers operating through California ports face unprecedented exposure from whistleblower allegations of customs fraud. California businesses at Los Angeles and Long Beach ports confront heightened scrutiny as the Department of Justice intensifies FCA enforcement against alleged misclassification schemes, undervaluation, and false country of origin claims. Qui tam relators filing under seal initiate government investigations that can remain confidential for years before defendants learn of allegations. Understanding FCA materiality standards, damages calculations, and available defenses has become essential for California companies in international trade. Our firm defends California importers and brokers against FCA qui tam actions.',
  services: 'Trembach Law Firm defends California importers against False Claims Act qui tam whistleblower lawsuits under 31 USC 3729-3733 alleging customs fraud or duty evasion. We respond to Civil Investigative Demands and DOJ investigations, defend qui tam litigation filed by former employees or competitors alleging classification or valuation fraud, negotiate settlements with DOJ and CBP minimizing liability, conduct internal investigations determining scope of alleged violations, and prepare affirmative defenses including lack of materiality and absence of scienter. FCA cases can result in treble damages making early intervention critical. Contact us upon learning of whistleblower investigation.',
