  intro: 'The Dominican Republic-Central America-United States Free Trade Agreement presents significant duty savings opportunities for California apparel importers sourcing from Costa Rica, El Salvador, Guatemala, Honduras, Nicaragua, and the Dominican Republic. With proper compliance under 19 CFR 10.2001-10.2060, textile importers can achieve duty-free treatment for qualifying goods meeting the Agreement\'s stringent yarn-forward rules of origin. However, CAFTA-DR\'s complex origin requirements—demanding that yarn formation, fabric production, and garment assembly all occur within the region—create substantial compliance challenges. The agreement provides limited exceptions through Tariff Preference Levels for specified quantities, Short Supply provisions, and cumulation rules for regional content. California apparel importers must maintain detailed supplier declarations, production records, and origin determinations. Our firm advises California textile importers on CAFTA-DR qualification and defends origin claims during CBP verifications.',
  services: 'Trembach Law Firm provides comprehensive CAFTA-DR textile and apparel compliance for California importers trading with Central America and Dominican Republic including yarn-forward rule compliance, tariff preference level quotas, textile visa categories, short supply claims, and certificate of origin requirements. We trace fiber and yarn to regional sources proving yarn-forward compliance, file short supply applications for unavailable inputs, prepare certificates with detailed fiber content and production location information, and defend textile origin claims during verifications. CAFTA-DR textile rules are highly technical and strictly enforced. Contact us for textile-specific qualification analysis.',
